            <groups_desc>Based on published literature, it is estimated that the incidence of HFS for all grades is 49%. A decrease of 50% or more in the incidence of HFS in patients receiving pyridoxine would be of clinical significance. A sample size of 27 patients per group was chosen as this would allow us to detect a difference between HFS incidence of 49% and 11.5% (alpha=0.05, two-sided, power=0.80). Interim analysis was conducted after 30 patients were enrolled and had evaluable HFS assessment data.</groups_desc>
